1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,800
Let's start with gathering.

2
00:00:01,800 --> 00:00:05,040
Data acquisition can happen in a variety of ways.

3
00:00:05,040 --> 00:00:06,900
In this case, you already acquired

4
00:00:06,900 --> 00:00:09,675
the data by downloading some files that were available.

5
00:00:09,675 --> 00:00:14,805
In other cases, you might need to get the data from an API or scrape it from a webpage.

6
00:00:14,805 --> 00:00:16,860
In many companies, they might have

7
00:00:16,860 --> 00:00:20,850
an existing database from which you can pull data and answer questions.

8
00:00:20,850 --> 00:00:25,035
You will also often need to combine data from multiple different formats.

9
00:00:25,035 --> 00:00:28,665
It's okay if some of these terms are unfamiliar to you.

10
00:00:28,665 --> 00:00:31,560
Your files are in a format called CSV,

11
00:00:31,560 --> 00:00:34,185
which stands for comma separated values.

12
00:00:34,185 --> 00:00:36,525
A CSV file is a text file.

13
00:00:36,525 --> 00:00:39,710
It's similar to a spreadsheet in terms of its tabular structure,

14
00:00:39,710 --> 00:00:43,415
but if you've ever seen if statements or other functions in your spreadsheets,

15
00:00:43,415 --> 00:00:45,740
this isn't possible in CSV files.

16
00:00:45,740 --> 00:00:47,770
They hold only the raw data.

17
00:00:47,770 --> 00:00:52,835
The contents of a CSV file are also very easy to process manually using code.

18
00:00:52,835 --> 00:00:54,275
Unlike for example,

19
00:00:54,275 --> 00:00:58,480
an XLSX file, which is the format used by Microsoft Excel.

20
00:00:58,480 --> 00:01:02,060
Let's take a look at one of your files which contains cancer data.

21
00:01:02,060 --> 00:01:04,765
Here's how the file looks like in Google spreadsheets.

22
00:01:04,765 --> 00:01:06,740
There's a row for each time a tumor was

23
00:01:06,740 --> 00:01:09,860
extracted and columns for different pieces of information,

24
00:01:09,860 --> 00:01:11,990
such as the ID, diagnosis,

25
00:01:11,990 --> 00:01:15,200
radius, texture, area, and smoothness.

26
00:01:15,200 --> 00:01:18,925
Now here's how the file looks like if you open it in a plain text editor.

27
00:01:18,925 --> 00:01:21,590
A text editor is a program like Notepad or

28
00:01:21,590 --> 00:01:24,515
sublime that shows exactly what's present in the file.

29
00:01:24,515 --> 00:01:28,520
As you can see, the actual contents of the file are very simple.

30
00:01:28,520 --> 00:01:34,105
The header row from the spreadsheet is present as the first line of the CSV file.

31
00:01:34,105 --> 00:01:39,845
The second row of the spreadsheet is the second line of the CSV file, and so on.

32
00:01:39,845 --> 00:01:43,340
Within each row, you'll see the first cell followed by a comma,

33
00:01:43,340 --> 00:01:44,870
followed by the second cell,

34
00:01:44,870 --> 00:01:47,305
followed by a comma, and so on.

35
00:01:47,305 --> 00:01:51,665
This makes CSVs very easy to process and programming languages like Python

36
00:01:51,665 --> 00:01:57,090
and packages such as pandas have specific functions for loading data from CSVs.

